'''Hejian''' ({{zh|t=河間 |s=河间 |p=Héjiān |w=Ho Chien}}; alternative [[romanization]]s: Ho Dsien [http://www.fas.harvard.edu/~chgis/maps/hist/zl_3.html], Ho-kien[-fou]) is a [[county-level city]] under the administration of the [[prefecture-level city]] of [[Cangzhou]], in the east-central part of [[Hebei]] province, China. {{asof|2004}}, the population was ca. 770,000 inhabitants and the city territory was {{convert|1333|km2|abbr=on}}. Hejian is situated along [[China National Highway 106]].
==History== [[File:Military station near the city of Chokien.jpg|thumb|"A military station near the city of Chokien", i.e. probably Hejian. (Ca. 1844)]]
[[Séraphin Couvreur]] (1835–1919) and [[Léon Wieger]] (1856–1933), two French Jesuit missionaries and renowned Sinologists worked at the Catholic Jesuit mission in Hejian.
The county contains the tomb of Chinese president [[Feng Guozhang]].
